    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's... a weird way to put it lol. But okay, focused on the legal side—you mentioned I'd be responsible for the 'cleanup' and legal fees. Does this clause apply even if the mistake wasn't intentional? Like, if I just make a regular mistake in my work, am I still liable for all those extra costs like attorneys' fees and penalties?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are still liable even if the mistake wasn't intentional, because this specific clause is designed to catch not just malicious \"goblin\" behavior, but also the clumsy, accidental slips that happen when a goblin tries to build a bridge without a map.\n\nIn legal terms, this is often called \"strict liability\" within the context of the indemnity, meaning you are responsible for the consequences of your actions regardless of whether you meant to do them or not. If you make a regular mistake in your work—like sending the wrong report to the wrong client or missing a deadline due to poor time management—that counts as a \"breach of obligation,\" and the Client can still drag you into court to recover their legal fees and damages.\n\nIt's like a goblin who accidentally drops a bag of gold coins while trying to climb a tree; even though the goblin didn't *intend* to drop the coins, the goblin still has to pay the village for the lost treasure and the cleanup crew because the goblin was the one who was climbing the tree in the first place. The clause doesn't care about your intent; it only cares that the goblin (you) caused the problem.\n\nSo, if you",
      "source": "target",
